{{Infobox scientist | name = Karen S. Cook | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age |1946|7|25|mf=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Sociology]] | workplaces = [[Stanford University]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = Stanford University | thesis_title = <!--(or | thesis1_title = and | thesis2_title = )--> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = <!--(or | thesis1_year = and | thesis2_year = )--> | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = Cooley-Mead Award (2004) | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Karen Schweers Cook''' (born July 25, 1946) is an American sociologist and the Ray Lyman Wilbur Professor of Sociology at [[Stanford University]], where she is also Vice-Provost for Faculty Development and Diversity and the director of the Institute for Research in the Social Sciences.
==Biography== Before becoming a member of the Stanford faculty in 1998, Cook was a department chair at the [[University of Washington]] and then the James B. Duke Professor of Sociology at [[Duke University]].<ref name=RWJF/> At Stanford, she is the Ray Lyman Wilbur Professor of Sociology at [[Stanford University]], Vice-Provost for Faculty Development and Diversity and the director of the Institute for Research in the Social Sciences.<ref name=Stanford/>
Cook has been elected to the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]], the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] and the [[National Academy of Sciences]].<ref name="AAAS">{{cite web|title=Cook, Karen|url=https://www.aaas.org/content/cook-karen|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Arts">{{cite web|title=Karen Schweers Cook|url=https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?s=karen+cook|website=www.amacad.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name="NAS">{{cite web|title=Karen Cook|url=http://www.nasonline.org/member-directory/members/15334.html|website=www.nasonline.org|publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> She received the Cooley-Mead Award from the [[American Sociological Association]] in 2004.<ref name=RWJF/> She was elected to the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2018.<ref>https://www.amphilsoc.org/blog/election-new-members-2018-spring-meeting</ref>
Cook is a co-editor of the ''[[Annual Review of Sociology]]''. She is a past president of the [[Pacific Sociological Association]] and a former vice president of the [[International Institute of Sociology]] and the [[American Sociological Association]].<ref name="RWJF">{{cite web|title=Karen S. Cook|url=http://healthpolicyscholars.org/karen-s-cook|website=healthpolicyscholars.org|publisher=[[Robert Wood Johnson Foundation]]|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> She was named to the [[Russell Sage Foundation]] Board of Trustees in 2012.<ref name="Stanford">{{cite web|title=Karen Cook|url=https://sociology.stanford.edu/people/karen-cook|website=sociology.stanford.edu|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref>
